# {{ project_name }}

Generated by the framework.

## Quickstart

```bash
uv sync
task hooks     # install pre-commit hooks
task dev       # full local stack over HTTPS — see "Local stack (HTTPS)" below
task test      # fast test run
task test:cov  # tests with coverage (>= 70%)
task lint      # ruff + mypy
```

## Quality gates

- TDD is the workflow — see `CLAUDE.md`. Tests are tiered: `tests/unit`, `tests/functional`, `tests/e2e`.
- Coverage gates by stage: pre-commit runs unit+functional at >=70% (`task test:cov`); CI runs all three at >=85% (`task test:cov:ci`).
- Pre-commit runs ruff, mypy, actionlint, shellcheck, gitleaks, file hygiene, and the coverage gate on every commit (`task hooks` to install).
- A Claude Code hook lints each Python file right after it is edited (`.claude/settings.json`).

## CI/CD

- `task ci` — local pre-flight: lint + the 85% coverage gate + pip-audit + OpenAPI export. Run before pushing.
- `task push` — pushes and triggers `.github/workflows/ci.yml`, the authoritative pipeline (a DAG, not a strict chain): integrity (seam) → then in parallel **lint** and **security** (pip-audit + full-history gitleaks) → then in parallel **tests** (unit/functional/e2e + 85% gate), the **image build**, and the **OpenAPI contract diff** → **review agents** (seam).
- `task openapi:export` — regenerate `openapi.json` after changing routes; commit it (CI fails on a stale or breaking spec). On a brand-new project, run this once and commit `openapi.json` before your first push, or the first `contract` CI job will fail by design.
- `task audit` — scan dependencies for CVEs. `.github/dependabot.yml` opens weekly update PRs.

## Deploy

`deploy-staging.yml` (on merge to `main`) builds+pushes the image, deploys via your strategy,
and runs four validation phases (smoke → sniff → E2E → k6 load) with automatic rollback;
`deploy-prod.yml` promotes the same image behind a manual approval gate. **You implement the
deploy strategy for your target** — see `DEPLOY.md` and `infra/deploy/README.md`. Run any tier
locally against a target: `SMOKE_TARGET=… task test:smoke` (and `test:sniff` / `test:load`,
or `E2E_TARGET=… uv run pytest tests/e2e`).

## Local stack (HTTPS)

> **Prerequisites:** run `task doctor` to check the host tools this needs — Docker, mkcert, uv, git{% if "react" in batteries %}, Node{% endif %}.

```bash
task certs     # one-time: install mkcert CA + issue localhost certs
task dev       # full stack at https://{{ project_slug }}.localhost (app + Traefik)
task dev:lite  # app only at http://localhost:8000 (no Traefik)
```

Service addresses are documented in `SERVICES.md`.

Each stack uses the compose project name `{{ project_slug }}`, so two clones or checkouts of
this repo get isolated containers, networks, and volumes. To run a second stack alongside the
first on the same machine, shift its host ports with `PORT_OFFSET`:

```bash
PORT_OFFSET=100 task dev       # shifts all host ports by 100 (app: 8100, Postgres: 5532, …)
PORT_OFFSET=100 task dev:lite  # lite variant with the same offset
```

Alternatively, set individual `*_HOST_PORT` variables in your `.env`. See `.env.example` for the
full list of overridable port variables.

### Multiple stacks behind a shared edge (`task dev:edge`)

`PORT_OFFSET` suits a handful of stacks. To run **many** (e.g. one per git worktree) without port
or `:443` collisions, bring the stack up **behind a shared reverse-proxy edge** instead:

```bash
STACK_INSTANCE={{ project_slug }}-wt1 task dev:edge   # up WITHOUT binding :443; a shared edge routes to it
task dev:edge:down                                    # tear this instance's stack down
```

In edge mode the stack keeps its Traefik **discovery labels** but runs no edge of its own; a single
box-wide edge discovers its containers over the `swiftwater-shared-edge` Docker network and routes
`https://<svc>-{{ project_slug }}-wt1.localhost` to them — so any number of stacks coexist behind one
edge under one wildcard `*.localhost` cert. Give each stack a distinct `STACK_INSTANCE` so its routes,
containers, and volumes never collide.

> **Prerequisite (you supply):** a conformant shared edge must already be running on the box — one that
> discovers the instance labels over `swiftwater-shared-edge` and terminates TLS with a `*.localhost`
> cert. `task dev:edge` fails fast with a clear message if none is present. This replaces the older
> hand-rolled "exclude Traefik + `PORT_OFFSET`" workaround.

### Upgrading from an earlier release

This release sets a per-project compose `name:` in `infra/compose/base.yml`, so an existing
local stack's compose project changes from `compose` to `{{ project_slug }}`. Your old
`compose_*` dev volumes (including the Postgres data volume) are orphaned — not migrated — and
the new stack starts with a fresh dev database. Re-seed local dev after upgrading:

```bash
task dev           # brings up the new stack and runs migrations
task db:seed       # loads seed data into the fresh database
```

`task db:migrate` and `task db:seed` are also available independently if needed. Production and
staging deploys are unaffected — `infra/compose/staging.yml` and `infra/compose/prod.yml` are
self-contained and do not include `infra/compose/base.yml`.

With the full `task dev` stack, observability is at: Grafana `http://localhost:3000` (SLO dashboard), Prometheus `http://localhost:9090`, Alertmanager `http://localhost:9093`. Alert rules and the dashboard are generated from the SLO definitions — run `task observability:gen` after changing them.

Application logs (structlog JSON) are shipped to Loki by Promtail and queryable in Grafana under the Loki datasource — e.g. `{service="app"}` (filter by `level`, find a request by its `correlation_id`).

Requests are traced with OpenTelemetry (enabled in the `dev` stack) and stored in Tempo — view traces in Grafana, and jump from a log line to its trace via the `trace_id` derived field (Loki→Tempo). Tracing is off in `lite`/local runs.

## Database

PostgreSQL + SQLAlchemy + Alembic. The `dev`/`lite`/`test` stacks bring up Postgres
automatically; on first `task dev` the app container runs pending migrations and loads
seed data (`seeds/items.json`) before serving — idempotently, so later runs skip
seeding. `task dev:reset` drops the volume and rebuilds from scratch.

- `task db:migrate` — apply pending migrations (`alembic upgrade head`)
- `task db:seed` — load seed data
- Schema changes: edit the models, then
  `uv run alembic revision --autogenerate -m "..."`. Never edit an applied migration —
  add a new one.

Tests run against a **real Postgres** (started automatically via testcontainers), so
**Docker is required to run the test suite**. The `test` Compose profile provides a
separate, ephemeral Postgres (`postgres-test`, reset every run) for the full E2E stack.

