## Authentication

Identity lives in the **control plane** (users / sessions / memberships); sessions are opaque,
server-side, and httpOnly-cookie-borne (never tenant-bound). Passwords are argon2id + an
application pepper; tokens are stored only as `HMAC-SHA256(token, session_pepper)`.

**Signup is FAIL-CLOSED by default** (this is the framework's deliberate opposite of an
"empty allowlist = open" default — a consumer must explicitly opt in):

| `APP_ENVIRONMENT` | `APP_SIGNUP_ALLOWLIST`     | `POST /auth/signup`              |
| ----------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| `prod`            | (any)                      | **404** — signup off entirely    |
| `staging`         | empty                      | **403** — denied (opt-in needed) |
| `staging`         | populated + email matches  | **201** — created                |
| `dev`             | (any)                      | **201** — open                   |

Opt into staging signups by populating `APP_SIGNUP_ALLOWLIST` (exact emails and/or `@domain`
suffixes). Collisions on email *or* slug return one generic **409** that never reveals which
collided (no account/tenant enumeration); login failures all return the same generic **401**.

**Login mints a brand-new session** — no caller-supplied session id is ever adopted, so session
fixation is structurally impossible. `/auth/set-password` redeems a single-use token and then
**deletes ALL of the user's sessions** (a credential reset must not leave old sessions live).

> **B-F11 — if you add a logged-in change-password or account-disable flow, it MUST replicate
> that session-invalidation step** (`delete Session WHERE user_id = …`). `/auth/set-password`
> already does it; any new credential-mutating route is on the hook to do the same, or stale
> sessions survive the credential change.

The session-cookie flags (httpOnly, `secure`, `SameSite=Lax`, optional parent `domain`) are set
in exactly one place — `multitenantauth/cookies.py:set_session_cookie`.
{%- endif %}

